    "direction": null,
    "content": "Three capacitors of capacitance 1.0, 2.0 and 5.0 $$\\mu$$F are connected in series to a 10 V source. The potential difference across the 2.0$$\\mu$$F capacitor is",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "$${{100} \\over {17}}$$V"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "$${{20} \\over {17}}$$V"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "$${{50} \\over {17}}$$V"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "10V"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "C"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "Image<br><br>When the capacitors are connected in series, the resultant capacitance of combination<br><br>$${1 \\over C} = {1 \\over {{C_1}}} + {1 \\over {{C_2}}} + {1 \\over {{C_3}}}$$<br><br>$$ = {1 \\over 1} + {1 \\over 2} + {1 \\over 5} = {{17} \\over {10}}\\mu F$$<br><br>$$C = {{10} \\over {17}}\\mu F$$<br><br>The charge will be same on all the capacitors in series<br><br>$$Q = CV = {{10} \\over {17}} \\times 10 = {{100} \\over {17}}$$<br><br>The potential difference across 2.0$$\\mu$$F capacitor<br><br>$$V' = {Q \\over C} = {{100/17} \\over 2} = {{50} \\over {17}}$$ volt",
    "topic": "combination-of-capacitors",
    "year": 2017,
    "yearKey": "wb-jee-2017",
    "difficulty": null
  },
